ydock, Lancashire, England"},"en":{"about 1243–Deceased":"about 1243–Deceased","1243–Female":"1243–Deceased","1245–1322":"1245–1322","1250–Male":"1250–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1240–1322":"1240–1322","1255–1330":"1255–1330","1257–1322":"1257–1322","1225–1299":"1225–1299","1225–1312":"1225–1312","1242":"1242","1330":"1330","1240":"1240","1250":"1250","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1225":"1225","1312":"1312","1257":"1257","1322":"1322","1245":"1245","1299":"1299","1255":"1255","1243":"1243","about 1243":"about 1243","1317":"1317","Bold, Lancashire, England, UK":"Bold, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Haydock, Lancashire, England":"Haydock, Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Haydock","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Haddock   1 and 2.","Americanized form of Czech or Polish   Hejduk  , Polish, Slovak, Rusyn (from Slovakia and Poland), or Czech   Hajduk  , and of their Hungarian cognate <b>Hajdók</b>. Compare   Hydock  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Haddock","meanings":["English:","variant of the Lancashire surname   Haydock  , a habitational name from a place so called near Liverpool, which is probably named from Welsh <i>heiddog</i> ‘characterized by barley’.","from the Middle English personal name <i>Addoc</i>, a pet form of Old English <i>Æddi</i> (itself perhaps derived from one of the names in <i>ēad</i> ‘wealth, prosperity’), with prosthetic <i>H-</i>."]}]},{"name":"Ellen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Helen  , although now no longer associated with that name. Initial <i>H-</i> tended to be added and dropped rather capriciously, leading to many doublets (  compare for example  Esther   and   Hester  ). It is also sometimes used as a short form of   Eleanor  , to which, however, it is unrelated."],"variants":[{"name":"Eleanor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":16,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":47,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":72,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused